Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which supports the euro by setting constraints on the size of budget deficits of Union members, is in danger.
As the heavy weight of the Union, Germany has failed to honor its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
In addition, it has used its political weight to cover the warning signal preceding its deficit, set up by the European Commission in accordance with the Stability Pact terms.
Today it is France that is playing the bad boy.
:#2 The second biggest player in the Union, somewhat reluctant, has officially come to declare that it cannot meet its commitment to reduce the budget deficit one year after small Ireland received an official warning about its fiscal policies despite its budget surpluses and in a very severe manner.
:#2 Thus, four years after its signing, the Stability Pact is a real disaster.
:#3 In fact, Europe seems very much affected by the discussions aimed at eliminating it as well as the discussions aiming to amend it.
:#4 And rightly so: the Pact is badly designed and poorly implemented.
:#5 Limiting the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and without considering the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
Admitting this fact, the architects of the pact have worsened the situation by adopting two "poorly thought-out" solutions.
They introduced a safeguard clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is virtually impossible in practice.
Fearing that serious slowdowns could undermine the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit equaled zero deficit.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a budget projection for the next two years demonstrating how budget equilibrium will be achieved over time.
Germany's commitment for 2002 was taken in 2001, when its economy was developing at a reasonable pace.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The minister of finance, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a budgetary tightening fiscal policy.
The Commission, seeking to project itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation of France is different.
In election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, especially about tax reduction.
In a country where the tax burden is high, not only is it a matter of political intelligence, but also economic intelligence, given the reduced budgetary expenditures.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain financial privileges financed by the state, and thus, budget cuts are definitively poorly perceived.
Therefore, France cannot meet its targets and the Commission has expressed its annoyance.
But France has mastered the art of defying the Union's laws.
Political maneuvers will follow, inevitably.
Economists and cynics are not surprised.
The goal of the pact—to establish fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency—is entirely justified.
However, having lost control of their national monetary policies, members of the Union now have only one macroeconomic tool left: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, it's not easy to reconcile these two things.
The Stability Pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the 3% target set by Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians in office.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look far.
The monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the last ten years, monetary policy truly succeeded.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it is enough to delegate this policy to a competent group, the central bank, by giving it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Aware that any deviation must be fixed in the future, it must exercise common sense.
This has turned out to be one of the major improvements in monetary policy in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Of course, some fear losing democracy in the process.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy has two very different objectives.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure in terms of spending and revenues.
The decisions concerning these issues cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and subject to parliamentary approval and management
The second is macroeconomic: it is about defining the budget balance to manage fluctuations cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain full control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its deficit or surplus decisions, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure its effectiveness, the status of such a Committee and its mandates must achieve consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulations, without any political decision-making, but simply by relying on common sense.
